I believe the reason why we see the lag is that point is drawn inside `draw` function which is invoked repeatedly independent from `mouse-moved` callback. For example.
1. On millisecond X `mouse-moved` was called and new x and y were saved in atom.
2. On millisecond X+100 `draw` was invoked, which drew the point in old x and y position. In the same time you already moved mouse cursor away from the old point. 

The same behaviour you can see in Processing itself:

``` java
int x;
int y;

void setup() {
  size(200, 200);
  smooth();
}

void draw() {
  background(125);
  strokeWeight(20);
  stroke(10);
  point(x, y);
}

void mouseMoved() {
  x = mouseX;
  y = mouseY;
}
```

As for how to solve it - you can draw point inside `mouse-moved` itself. This will make the lag much less noticeable.

> I am just assuming there is some meaningful difference between them.

It does not matter (as far as I understand Processing.js code). Because if you check https://github.com/processing-js/processing-js/blob/master/src/Processing.js (be careful! a lot of code!) for `Drawing3D.prototype.size` you can't find something different than

```
function getGLContext(canvas) {
          var ctxNames = ['experimental-webgl', 'webgl', 'webkit-3d'],
              gl;

          for (var i=0, l=ctxNames.length; i<l; i++) {
            gl = canvas.getContext(ctxNames[i], {antialias: false, preserveDrawingBuffer: true});
            if (gl) {
              break;
            }
          }

          return gl;
        }
```

for initializing context of canvas element for 3D drawing mode. Therefore is no difference between `p3d` and `opengl` modes for Processing.js.

I think this is just the inheritance from Java version of Processing.

