I think it probably all _is_ an intentional design decision (and not a bad one, given the hardware ecosystem out there).

The specific bug that motivated my check involved the display of a supposedly "400px" square `quil` sketch on a HiDPI iOS device in portrait mode &c &c &c... it gets pretty specific.

The reasonable-feeling fix, for me, is to work with the CSS on the pages where such `quil` sketches are embedded. So here's the approach I'm using now, and it seems to have fixed the issue, for me, and _for the moment_:

``` css
.quil-sketch {
  height: 0;
  width: 100%;
  padding-bottom: 100%;
}

canvas {
  max-width: 100%;
  max-height: 100%;
}
```

That is, I specified the `div` host style to "want to be square", and forced all `canvas` sizes to have maxima as indicated. It feels like there will be a problem some day farther on, maybe as soon as I want to have a non-square `quil` sketch, but for now this handles my problem on iOS with overflow and scaling.

Perhaps though the "real bug" is that this should probably be better documented, since it seems to be (1) a good thing to have pretty graphics on expensive hardware, but (2) a nasty thing to try to debug if you don't notice the `width` tricks in `p5.js`....
